result.execSummary:
The defendant Jason Edward Rodriguez was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Jason Edward Rodriguez is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Jason Edward Rodriguez was found guilty of Reckless Driving-Cause Great Bodily Harm, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.62(4).
  • Jason Edward Rodriguez was found guilty of Injury by Intoxicated Use/Vehicle, a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.25(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Defendant Jason Edward Rodriguez in court.  Attorney Jonathan A. LaVoy in court for Jason Edward Rodriguez.  Attorney Kimberly Dorice Schoepp in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Case in court for sentencing.  Statements made by the State, Defense Counsel, and Defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 36 MONTHS with 20 days credit, CONCURRENT to Count 3; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 18 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 18 MONTHS. 

AS TO COUNT 3:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 90 MONTHS with 20 days credit, CONCURRENT to Count 1; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 42 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 48 MONTHS. 

Court finds the defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program and the WI Substance Abuse program.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION: 
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any recommended treatment. 
- Provide DNA sample. 
- Full-time work/school. 
- Complete 200 hours of community service. 

Court set restitution at zero.  Court ordered the defendant to pay all court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA) during the term of extended supervision.  DOC is NOT to collect during initial confinement.  Failure to pay shall result in a civil judgment. If revoked, Court ordered that all court costs, fees, and surcharges be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections in an amount or percentage the Department (DOC) determines to be reasonable and as a condition of extended supervision.  DOC shall collect those sums. Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.

20 day appeal rights given. Firearm and voting warnings given.

Defendant Jason Edward Rodriguez in court with Attorney Jonathan A. LaVoy.  Kimberly Dorice Schoepp appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Case in court for plea hearing.  Parties have reached an agreement.  Plea negotiations set forth on the record and agreed upon by the parties.

AS TO COUNTS 1 AND 3:
Defendant changes pleas to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's pleas.  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Pursuant to plea negotiations and on the motion of the State, Court ordered COUNT 2 DISMISSED BUT READ IN for the purpose of sentencing and COUNT 4 DISMISSED by operation of law.  

Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon, he may never own or possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that he may not vote until his civil rights have been restored.  Court ordered a Pre-Sentence Investigation with recommendation upon request from the parties. Case adjourned for sentencing in Branch 40.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for October 21, 2022 at 09:00 am.
